\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
Such an inhomogeneous Laplace equation is usually referred to as Poisson
 equation and it is elliptic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Heat flow equation (
\lang ngerman
Wärmeleitungsgleichung
\lang english
): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\left(t,x\right)$
\end_inset

 be the temperature at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and position 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial_{t}\varphi\left(t,x\right) & =\upDelta\varphi\left(t,x\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is a parabolic equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The Schrödinger equation is a parabolic equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ii\hbar\partial_{t}\psi\left(t,x\right) & =\left(-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\upDelta+V\right)\psi\left(t,x\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Additionally to the the heat flow equation there is the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, but more important there is a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ii$
\end_inset

 in front of the partial derivative.
 The time-independent Schrödinger equation is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E\psi\left(x\right) & =\left(-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\upDelta+V\right)\psi\left(x\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is similar to the Poisson equation and also elliptic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The wave equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\partial_{t}^{2}-\upDelta_{x}\right)\psi\left(t,x\right) & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

is hyperbolic.
 We will consider it in the lecture 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Partial Differential Equations II
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Maxwell's equations: 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(t,x\right)$
\end_inset

 is the electric field and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\left(t,x\right)$
\end_inset

 the magnetic field.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{div}\left(E\right) & =4\pi\varrho &  & \text{Gauss law}\\
\text{rot}\left(E\right) & =-\partial_{t}B &  & \text{Maxwell}\\
\text{div}\left(B\right) & =0\\
\text{rot}\left(B\right) & =4\pi j-\partial_{t}E &  & \text{Faraday}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is a system of 8 partial differential equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Einstein's field equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
R_{ij}-\frac{1}{2}Rg_{ij} & =4\pi\kappa T_{ij}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is a geometric partial differential equation.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the Ricci curvature, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 the scalar curvature and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ij}$
\end_inset

 the energy-momentum tensor.
 It is a system of 10 partial differential equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Equations of relativistic quantum mechanics:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(-\partial_{t}^{2}+\upDelta\right)\psi & =m^{2}\psi
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is the Klein-Gordon equation with the mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ii\gamma^{j}\partial_{j}\psi & =m\psi
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is the Dirac equation, a system of 4 complex-valued or 8 real-valued
 partial differential equations for a particle with spin 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

