\emph on
multi-index
\emph default
.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs{\alpha}:=k$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\emph on
order
\emph default
 or 
\emph on
absolute value
\emph default
 of the multi-index.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this we can write differentials of order 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\DD^{\alpha} & :=\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{i_{1}}}\cdots\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{i_{k}}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

and homogeneous polynomials of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 in the components of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\left(x^{1},\ldots,x^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{\alpha} & :=x^{i_{1}}\cdots x^{i_{k}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C^{\infty}\left(\mathbb{R}^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r,s\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 we define the 
\emph on
Schwartz norm
\emph default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\norm f_{r,s} & :=\sum_{\alpha,\abs{\alpha}\le r}\sum_{\beta,\abs{\beta}\le s}\sup_{x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}}\abs{x^{\alpha}\DD^{\beta}f\left(x\right)}
\end{align}

\end_inset

For example for 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0=s$
\end_inset

 we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\norm f_{0,0} & =\sup_{x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}}\abs{f\left(x\right)}=\norm f_{C^{0}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
