\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 with boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 With the Laplacian
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\upDelta & =\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x_{1}^{2}}+\ldots+\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x_{n}^{2}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

the Laplace equation can be written as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\upDelta u & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The inhomogeneous Laplace equation is called Poisson equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\upDelta u & =f
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For both one needs to specify boundary conditions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\Omega$
\end_inset

 to get a unique solution.
