\begin_layout Standard
Any solution 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 of the Dirichlet problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\upDelta u & =f & u\big|_{\partial\Omega} & =\varphi
\end{align*}

\end_inset

has the representation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u\left(y\right) & =\int_{\partial\Omega}\varphi\left(x\right)\nabla_{\nu}G\left(x,y\right)\dd\mu_{\partial\Omega}\left(x\right)+\int_{\Omega}G\left(x,y\right)f\left(x\right)\dd\mu\left(x\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We define:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u\left(y\right) & :=\int_{\partial\Omega}\varphi\left(x\right)\nabla_{\nu}G\left(x,y\right)\dd\mu_{\partial\Omega}\left(x\right)+\int_{\Omega}G\left(x,y\right)f\left(x\right)\dd\mu\left(x\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is symmetric, 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(x,y\right)=G\left(y,x\right)$
\end_inset

, the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\upDelta_{x}G\left(x,y\right)=\delta^{\left(n\right)}\left(x-y\right)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\upDelta_{y}G\left(x,y\right)=\delta^{\left(n\right)}\left(x-y\right)$
\end_inset

 as well.
 As a consequence, a formal computation gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\upDelta_{y}u\left(y\right) & =\int_{\partial\Omega}\varphi\left(x\right)\nabla_{\nu}\delta^{\left(n\right)}\left(x-y\right)\dd\mu_{\partial\Omega}\left(x\right)+\int_{\Omega}\delta^{\left(n\right)}\left(x-y\right)f\left(x\right)\dd\mu\left(x\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 the first term vanishes, so we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\upDelta_{y}u\left(y\right) & =f\left(y\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This formal calculation can be made rigorous, once an explicit Green's function
 is given.
